ion to tone, while others assert that it is syllable stress or length. All tonal languages not classified as simple have a complex tone system. There are four (or five, when we count the neutral tone) well-documented tones in Mandarin Chinese, so WALS classifies it as a language with a complex tone system. English, on the other hand, has no tones. %0a%3c %0a%3c I wonder if the presence of tones in a language makes it harder to learn for native English speakers. I grew up speaking English and Marathi, two atonal languages. I learned Spanish, another atonal language, in elementary school, and Mandarin Chinese, a tonal language, in high school. I found Spanish pronunciation much easier to grasp, mostly because of the fact that the tones in Mandarin Chinese (especially the first two of four) are difficult for my ear to distinguish. Now, in my case, this perceived disparity in difficulty could be due to the fact that it's much easier to learn a language when one is a small child than when one is a teenager. But it still makes sense that learning a language with features that one isn’t familiar with would present a greater challenge, all other things being equal. %0a%3c %0a%3c Sources:%0a%3c %0a%3c Ian Maddieson. 2013. Tone. In Dryer, Matthew S. & Haspelmath, Martin (eds.) The World Atlas of Language Structures Online. Leipzig: Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology. Available online at %3chttp://wals.info/chapter/13>, accessed 10 Feb 2021.%0a%3c %0a%3c Mandarin Chinese. 2020, Feb 8. In Wikipedia. Available online at %3chttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mandarin_Chinese>, accessed 8 Feb 2021.%0a%3c %0a%3c Moran, Steven & McCloy, Daniel (eds.) 2019.  PHOIBLE 2.0. Jena: Max Planck Institute for the Science of Human History. Available online at %3chttp://phoible.org>, accessed 8 Feb 2021.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
